  "text": "Let the spacetime (M, g) be strongly future asymptotically predictable and let J + be the future null infinity (see [CITATION_1] + (S) is an n − 1 dimensional Lipschitz topological submanifold of M and is achronal. Since a Cauchy horizon is Lipschitz it follows from a theorem of Rademacher that it is differentiable almost everywhere (i.e. differentiable except for a set of n − 1 dimensional measure zero). This does not exclude the possibility that the set of non-differentiable points is a dense subset of the horizon. In this section we shall give examples of such a behaviour.",
